Reflection Assignment 9
------------------------
Designing the domain model and class diagram presented several challenges. One of the main difficulties was deciding the appropriate level of abstraction. 
Initially, it was unclear whether to combine certain concepts such as Student and UserAccount into a single class. However, separating them allowed for 
better representation of authentication and user identity, which aligns with real-world systems.

Another challenge was defining relationships between classes. Determining whether to use association, aggregation, or composition required careful consideration. 
For example, the relationship between Module and Assignment was modeled as a strong association because assignments cannot exist without a module. Similarly, 
Assignment and Deadline were tightly coupled, as each assignment must have a deadline.

Method definitions also required thoughtful design. It was important to ensure that methods reflected system functionality defined in previous assignments. 
For instance, methods like create(), updateStatus(), and send() were derived directly from functional requirements and use cases. 
This ensured consistency across the system.

Aligning the class diagram with previous assignments was critical. The use cases defined earlier guided the identification of system operations, 
while state diagrams helped define object behaviors. Activity diagrams influenced how interactions between classes were structured. 
This integration ensured that the class diagram was not isolated but part of a continuous design process.

Trade-offs were also made during the design process. For example, inheritance was considered but not heavily used to avoid unnecessary complexity. 
Instead, simpler associations were preferred to maintain clarity and readability. This decision reflects a balance between theoretical design and practical implementation.

Another trade-off involved simplifying certain components such as Dashboard and Session. While these could be expanded into more complex structures, 
they were kept minimal to align with the project’s scope as an individual assignment.

Overall, this assignment improved understanding of object-oriented design principles, including encapsulation, modularity, and separation of concerns. 
It highlighted the importance of designing systems that are both functional and maintainable. The process also reinforced the value of traceability, 
ensuring that all components of the system align with requirements and user needs.

